<div id="review_2477711997" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2477711997" />
    <a title="Kelley" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/29588908-kelley"><img alt="Kelley" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1548895841p2/29588908.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2477711997?book_show_action=true">Aug 17, 2018</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Kelley" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Kelley" href="/user/show/29588908-kelley">Kelley</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9780714861159" href="/book/show/9712321-nicholas">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2477711997" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer6879857048259081339">Right about the time Beverly Cleary was bringing Ramona to life, Goscinny and Sempe were introducing the French world to Nicholas. In the last decade or so, English readers have finally gotten the chance to meet him.<br/><br/>In some dreamworld where the two children could cross paths, they would find in each other sweet commiseration for the miseries of childhood inflicted by adults who just don’t understand.<br/><br/>Nicholas faithfully reports everything just as he sees it in his world of school, home and the em</span>
  <span id="freeText6879857048259081339" style="display:none">Right about the time Beverly Cleary was bringing Ramona to life, Goscinny and Sempe were introducing the French world to Nicholas. In the last decade or so, English readers have finally gotten the chance to meet him.<br /><br />In some dreamworld where the two children could cross paths, they would find in each other sweet commiseration for the miseries of childhood inflicted by adults who just don’t understand.<br /><br />Nicholas faithfully reports everything just as he sees it in his world of school, home and the empty lot. Like most young children, he is an absolutist and a literalist.<br /><br />The day of a school inspection, the teacher warns against speaking or laughing out of turn. The inspector opens his presentation with a joke.<br /><br />“It’s a pity our teacher had told us not to laugh without permission, because we could hardly restrain ourselves. … The inspector laughed a lot, but then he didn’t need anyone’s permission. However, when he saw that the whole class was quite quiet he put his eyebrows back into place and coughed …” <br /><br />Nicholas won’t let you lose track of his gang. The key members are reintroduced the first time they appear in every chapter.<br /><br />“Alec is my friend who is very fat and who eats all the time, perhaps I may have mentioned him before,” he says three pages from the end of the book. Yes, he had.<br /><br />“Cuthbert is top of the class and teacher’s pet and we aren’t all that mad about him only we can’t hit him much because of his glasses.”<br /><br />When the teacher leaves the room once and asks Cuthbert to keep an eye on things, Cuthbert instructs the other boys to work on a math problem. <br /><br />“So Matthew asked if he was out of his tiny mind,” Nicholas reports. <br /><br />Teachers, parents and principals are traumatized by the fights and pranks and name-calling. Nicholas is always confused by that. <br /><br />In one ball game, someone’s crying, someone just got kicked in the shins, and someone else’s new shirt is torn. “Eddie, who’d been waiting patiently in his own goal, got fed up and started punching the noses closest to him, which happened to belong to his own side. We were all shouting and running around and we were having a really fabulous time!”<br /><br />You really should join the fun.<br /><br /><br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="6879857048259081339" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

