  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_478623216" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/478623216" />
    <a title="Cruth" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/12723605-cruth"><img alt="Cruth" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1392864210p2/12723605.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/478623216?book_show_action=true">Dec 15, 2012</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Cruth" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Cruth" href="/user/show/12723605-cruth">Cruth</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Hardcover 9780714845296" href="/book/show/128654.Nicholas">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/12723605-cruth?shelf=read-aloud">read-aloud</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/12723605-cruth?shelf=childrens-chapter-book">childrens-chapter-book</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer478623216" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer4707654778306198494">Nicholas - written by Rene Goscinny, (who wrote Asterix) and illustrated by Jean-Jacques Sempe.<br/><br/>Originally published in France, 1959, as &quot;Le petit Nicolas&quot;, this edition was first published in 2005 (my version from 2007). Translated by Anthea Bell.<br/><br/>I should admit outright I was never much of a fan of Asterix. I never really got the humour. Maybe &apos;cause I&apos;m a girl - my brothers all liked them. And so perhaps some of the story here is not my thing because it is so male-centric.<br/><br/>Each chapter stands as</span>
  <span id="freeText4707654778306198494" style="display:none">Nicholas - written by Rene Goscinny, (who wrote Asterix) and illustrated by Jean-Jacques Sempe.<br /><br />Originally published in France, 1959, as "Le petit Nicolas", this edition was first published in 2005 (my version from 2007). Translated by Anthea Bell.<br /><br />I should admit outright I was never much of a fan of Asterix. I never really got the humour. Maybe 'cause I'm a girl - my brothers all liked them. And so perhaps some of the story here is not my thing because it is so male-centric.<br /><br />Each chapter stands as a self contained story of around 6 pages (book has 127 pages, and 19 chapters).<br /><br />As a read aloud, it struggles. Told from a little boy's pov (Nicholas) and in his voice, we have many run on sentences. The frequency of them makes the story harder to follow. And more difficult for an early reader to read.<br /><br />Nicholas attends a boys school, and his friends are all boys. No female characters, and we have stereotypically male child scenarios. The boys physically fight, disobey the teacher, argue, call each other names (bullying/teasing). It is treated as normal behaviour and they do not have consequences. As a book from which children model behaviour - it isn't my cup of tea. In every story someone gets told off and cries, someone else is punched on the nose, and they are all having a really good time. I just don't get it.<br /><br />But the 6yo enjoys it. And the teen, who loved this book 7 years ago, is enjoying listening in. They like the slapstick-ish child humour, they read/hear the "naughty boy" scenarios and think "boy, wouldn't that be fun? but we so would get in trouble" or "boys are like that", and keep going. They see more in this book than I do.<br /><br />Illustrations are infrequent - we get a large illustrative drawing as we begin the chapter, small ones in the next pages. More text than drawing. But the images are lovely and whimsical. Definitely add to the book.<br /><br />The language itself uses a simple, easy vocabulary. No particularly difficult words. However, children would be confronted with "walls of text", which is often very off-putting. The ability of the child to concentrate on reading an entire page of text has to be learnt and practiced - you couldn't expect a too new reader to comfortably tackle "Nicholas".<br /><br />Overall, I liked it. It was an unusual, interesting read that appealed to the kids.<br /><br />Age (taking into account comprehension, concentration, language):<br />Read aloud - 6+<br />Read yourself - 9+</span>
  <a data-text-id="4707654778306198494" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


